Hospitals are bracing for millions of Americans to be hospitalized as part of the novel coronavirus outbreak. 
The American Hospital Association, which represents thousands of hospitals and health systems, hosted a webinar in February with its member hospitals and health systems. Business Insider obtained a copy of the slides presented. 
The presentation, titled "What healthcare leaders need to know: Preparing for the COVID-19" happened February 26, with representatives from the National Ebola Training and Education Center. 
As part of the presentation to hospitals, Dr. James Lawler, a professor at the University of Nebraska Medical Center gave his "best guess" estimates of how much the virus might spread in the US.
Lawler's estimates include:
4.8 million hospitalizations associated with the novel coronavirus
96 million cases overall in the US
480,000 deaths
Overall, the slide points out that hospitals should prepare for an impact to the system that's 10 times a severe flu season. ￼AHA webinar
The slide does not give a particular time frame.
The slide represents "his interpretation of the data available. It's possible that forecast will change as more information becomes available," a spokesman for Nebraska Medicine told Business Insider in an email. 
The American Hospital Association said the webinar reflects the views of the experts who spoke on it, not its own.
"The AHA regularly hosts webinars and conference calls that include a variety of voices and opinions that seek to provide relevant information to professionals at hospitals and health systems that are on the front lines of preparing for and protecting their patients and communities," a spokeswoman for the AHA told Business Insider in an emailed statement. "The slides you shared reflect the various perspectives of field experts and should not be attributed to the AHA."
In particular, the slide points out that hospitals should prepare for an impact to the system that's 10 times a severe flu season.

The Flu vs the Coronavirus

CDC reported 15 MILLION flu cases in the US in the 2019-2020 flu season. The US Center for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) released this data from the second week of 2020, at that point 10,000 people had died In the US and 180,000 people had been hospitalized during the 2019-2020 flu season. 82,400 cases of the coronavirus have been reported WORLD WIDE, vs 15,000,000 cases of the flu in the US alone. As of Thursday morning 2,804 people have died of the coronavirus WORLD WIDE vs 10,000 deaths from the flu in the US. All but 60 of the coronavirus deaths were in mainland China. There have been 60 reported cases of the coronavirus in the US with no reported deaths.
Prevention of the flu, wash your hands, practice the elbow cough, disinfect common surfaces, drink plenty of water, stay home if you are sick.

Prevention of the coronavirus....see above.

3. It is spread mostly on water droplets (coughs sneezes) and by touching things that an infected person touched.
4. The best precaution is washing hands and carrying around wipes. But that is the same for influenza.
5. The velocity of numbers of Wuhan CoV infections is rapid but nothing like some other pandemics in the past. The first case of Spanish flu in 1918 was in March. By the following year 100 million infected and 20 million dead. Wuhan is not going to be that.

author: jkjdc02
comment:
I want to help with some facts about this coronavirus.
1. It is basically a SARS coronavirus. The genetic sequence is very similar to SARS CoV in 2003 and this one also emerged through bats. SARS in 2003 had a higher mortality rate than Wuhan virus. This virus is not a “leaked” lab strain nor is it biowarfare. Those conspiracies are not true and just an attempt to politicize this infection. How do we know? We know the sequence in humans and bats.
2. As with many respiratory viral infections a lot of these 2% deaths are elderly and small children. Normal healthy robust immune systems have a much much lower mortality rate.
3. It is spread mostly on water droplets (coughs sneezes) and by touching things that an infected person touched.
4. The best precaution is washing hands and carrying around wipes. But that is the same for influenza.
5. The velocity of numbers of Wuhan CoV infections is rapid but nothing like some other pandemics in the past. The first case of Spanish flu in 1918 was in March. By the following year 100 million infected and 20 million dead. Wuhan is not going to be that.
6. This coronavirus is not going to survive attached to parcel shipped from China. No real danger in goods coming from infected countries.
7. A vaccine is likely within 18 months.
8. The original SARS CoV in 2003 was gone within a year. And it had a higher mortality rate than Wuhan CoV and China did a crappier job with quarantine in 2003.
9. The current 2019 influenza has already killed 15,000 in the US alone. Wuhan has killed no one in the US. It is no where near as deadly as yearly influenza.
10. Don’t eat bats!
Relax. Wash your hands. And don’t play with bats. We will survive this. Influenza is much scarier.

"After 28 years and five Grand Slam titles, though, I’m ready to scale another mountain -- to compete on a different type of terrain," she wrote.

Her goodbye letter to the sport took readers through her journey from early formative years starting out in Russia, moving to Florida to pursue her athletic dreams and ultimately hailed her "mental fortitude" as her strongest weapon and key to her success on the court.

The five-time Grand Slam winner notched her top titles at the Wimbledon in 2004 -- when she was just 17 and defeated top-seeded Serena Williams -- the U.S. Open in 2006, the Australian Open in 2008, and two French Open wins at Roland Garros in 2012 and 2014.

A representative for Sharapova told ABC News that she will not be commenting beyond the essay at this time. "...as I embark on my next chapter," she wrote, "I want anyone who dreams of excelling in anything to know that doubt and judgment are inevitable: You will fail hundreds of times, and the world will watch you. Accept it. Trust yourself. I promise that you will prevail."

author: abcnews
comment:
The Emmett Till Anti-lynching Act, a bill to make lynching a hate crime under federal law, passed the House on Wednesday, making it the first attempt since 1900 poised to successfully make its way through Congress.
-
The vote was 410-4.
-
The legislation is named for Emmett Till, a 14-year-old African American boy who was kidnapped, beaten and lynched in 1955 after he was accused of whistling at a white woman.
Rep. Bobby Rush, who introduced the bill in January 2019, said it will finally outlaw "an American evil."
-
Lynchings were used in the U.S., predominantly in the South, from the 1880s to 1960s to terrorize black Americans. From 1882-1968, 4,743 lynchings occurred in the U.S., with 3,446 involving victims who were black, according to the NAACP.
-
Rush said the bill is expected to pass the Senate by the end of the week, before the end of Black History Month, and then makes its way to the Oval Office.
-
Asked if they believed Trump would sign the bill, Rep. Karen Bass said, "How could he not?"

"You were a darling to many and we have lost you to [a] brain tumor at such a tender age," the school tweeted. "Rest in Perfect Peace dear."
-
Waligwa starred in the 2016 Disney film "Queen of Katwe," a biographical film about Ugandan chess player Phiona Mutesi, who came from the slums to be one of the top players in the world. Waligwa played Gloria, Mutesi's friend and fellow chess player who says in chess, "the small one can become the big one."
-
The movie was a hit among Ugandan audiences who saw local actors on the same screen as Hollywood stars like Lupita Nyong'o and David Oyelowo.
-
Oyelowo shared his condolences on Instagram: "She was a ball of light in @queenofkatwemovie and in life. Her battle with a brain tumor was humbling to witness. Her light will live on."
-
(Disney is the parent company of ABC News.)

-

-
Bong also thanked another fellow nominee, Quentin Tarantino.
-
"When people in the U.S. were not familiar with my films Quentin always put my films on his list," he said through the interpreter.
-
